My Brothers of Choice,  <br><br>
I have given much thought to the words.  I will first address  Ed.  Cook your words will require a lot more thought, because we think so much alike.<br><br>
&quot;Cognition and Effect&quot;  I can agree with the premise that  the more you think the less emotion you feel because I am  living proof of the hypothesis.  The caveat I must give is;  this doesn't hold true if your thoughts are directed toward  those experiences which elicit strong emotion.  I believe we experience this emotion either on the conscious or subconscious  level.  The resultant stresses may not be perceived as emotions, or suppressed through denial.  We may not accept the emotional response, a defense mechanism,  but the stresses are still loaded into the system.  If we saturate  the conscious level with thought, work, play and all, we may suppress  the subconscious.  A false equilibrium is achieved.<br><br>
Good thoughts good feelings, bad thoughts bad feelings, I am O.K.  with that one.  Lets add another.  Diffused thoughts your fair game. I usually find that time you are least focused, your guard is down, the overwhelming experiences flood in. These can be damned up  by the defense mechanisms waiting on a opportunity.  This the time the speed of the onset  and the weight of the volumn takes us by surprise and away we go. These diffused thoughts can come at anytime when we are distracted enough to lose that focus which protects us.<br><br>
Suppose that the time of diffused thoughts can only occur  when you do not execute control.  You can control bad thoughts  and good thoughts.  Your thinking is diffused because you lose  control.<br><br>
Fear revolves around lack of control.  When we are focused  on any thought we are in control.  Diffused thinking leads to fear. I will accept confused thinking in the definition of diffused thoughts.<br><br>
Lets explore how fear, graduated levels revolves around the  lack of control.<br><br>

